<p>The <b>fight-or-flight response</b>, also called the <b><i>fright</i>, fight or flight response</b>, <b>hyperarousal</b> or the <b>acute stress response</b>, was first described by <a href="/wiki/Walter_Cannon" title="Walter Cannon" class="mw-redirect">Walter Cannon</a> in 1915.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> His theory states that animals react to threats with a general discharge of the <a href="/wiki/Sympathetic_nervous_system" title="Sympathetic nervous system">sympathetic nervous system</a>, priming the animal for <a href="/wiki/Fighting" title="Fighting" class="mw-redirect">fighting</a> or fleeing. This response was later recognized as the first stage of a <a href="/wiki/General_adaptation_syndrome" title="General adaptation syndrome" class="mw-redirect">general adaptation syndrome</a> that regulates <a href="/wiki/Stress_(medicine)" title="Stress (medicine)" class="mw-redirect">stress</a> responses among vertebrates and other organisms.</p>
